{{Infobox NRHP | name = Masonic Temple Building-Temple Theater | nrhp_type = | image = Masonic Temple Building-Temple Theater.jpg | caption = Masonic Temple Building | location= 47 Saint Helens Ave., [[Tacoma, Washington]] | coordinates = {{coord|47|15|43|N|122|26|39|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Washington | built = 1927 | architect = [[Ambrose J. Russell|Russell, Ambrose J.]] | architecture = Late 19th And 20th Century Revivals, Renaissance | added = April 29, 1993 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | mpsub = {{NRHP url|id=64500706|title=Movie Theaters in Washington State MPS}} | refnum = 93000357<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }} [[File:Masonic Temple Building-Temple Theater 01.jpg|thumb|left|The Landmark from a different angle]] The '''Landmark Convention Center''' in [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]], Washington (Historically known as the '''Masonic Temple Building''', the '''Temple Theater''', '''Helig's Theater''', and '''John Hamrick's Temple Theater''') is located at 47 St. Helens Avenue. It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1993. [[Ambrose J. Russell]] is credited as the architect of the meeting hall and theater. It is said to be in a [[Renaissance style]] and Late 19th And 20th Century Revival style, and said to have had its "period of significance" between 1925 and 1949.<ref>[http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/WA/Pierce/state2.html #93000357] National Register of Historic Places</ref>
For many years the building served as a meeting hall for local area [[Masonic lodge]]s. Today, no lodges meet in the building and it has been converted into a commercial catering and convention Center.<ref>[http://www.tacomaslandmark.com/ Landmark Catering and Convention Center website]</ref> On Feb 5, 2018, the convention center ownership decided to not host a meeting organized by the Department of the Interior, canceling it with less than 24-hours notice due to "concern for public safety."
