{{taxobox |image = |regnum = [[Plantae]] |unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]] |unranked_classis = [[Monocots]] |unranked_ordo = [[Commelinids]] |ordo = [[Poales]] |familia = [[Bromeliaceae]] |subfamilia = [[Tillandsioideae]] |genus = ''[[Vriesea]]'' |species = '''''V. friburgensis''''' |binomial = ''Vriesea friburgensis'' |binomial_authority = Mez |synonyms_ref=<ref name=p/> |synonyms=*''Vriesea paludosa'' <small>L.B.Sm.</small> *''Vriesea tucumanensis'' <small>Mez</small> *''Vriesea caldasiana'' <small>Mez</small> *''Vrieseida foetida'' <small>[[Rojas Acosta]]</small> *''Vriesea argentinensis'' <small>Speg.</small> |}}
'''''Vriesea friburgensis''''' is a [[species (biology)|species]] in the [[genus (biology)|genus]] ''[[Vriesea]]''. This species is an [[epiphyte]] [[Native plant|native]] to [[Bolivia]], [[Paraguay]], [[Argentina]], and [[Brazil]].<ref name=p>[http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=271819 Kew Checklist of Selected Plant Families]</ref><ref>[http://www.selby.org/clientuploads/pdf_files/BoliviaBrom.pdf Checklist of Bolivian Bromeliaceae] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129222456/http://www.selby.org/clientuploads/pdf_files/BoliviaBrom.pdf |date=2010-11-29 }} Retrieved 21 October 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.dpi.inpe.br/referata/arq/22_Rafael_Bromelias/Bromelia_Mata_Atlantica.pdf BROMELIACEAE DA MATA ATLÂNTICA BRASILEIRA] retrieved 22 October 2009</ref>
Three varieties are recognized:<ref name=p/>
#''Vriesea friburgensis'' var. ''friburgensis'' - eastern + southern Brazil #''Vriesea friburgensis'' var. ''paludosa'' <small>(L.B.Sm.) L.B.Sm.</small> - southeastern Brazil from São Paulo to Rio Grande do Sul #''Vriesea friburgensis'' var. ''tucumanensis'' <small>(Mez) L.B.Sm.</small> - most of species range
==Cultivars== * [[Vriesea Jubilation|''Vriesea'' 'Jubilation']]<ref name=j/> * [[Vriesea Little Dumplin'|''Vriesea'' 'Little Dumplin'']]<ref name=j/> * [[xVrieslandsia Red Dawn|''xVrieslandsia'' 'Red Dawn']]<ref name=j>[http://www.bsi.org/brom_info/cultivar/bcr.html BSI Cultivar Registry] Retrieved 11 October 2009</ref>
==Ecology== The large [[infructescence]]s of the plant dry up and may remain standing for a year or more, during which time they are inhabited by a variety of insect species and other arthropods. Several species of [[ant]]s, [[termite]]s, and [[bee]]s build nests in the dry fruiting structure. Surveys have revealed the nests of ants in the genera ''[[Camponotus]]'', ''[[Pseudomyrmex]]'', and ''[[Solenopsis (ant)|Solenopsis]]'', and termites of the genera ''[[Cortaritermes]]'' and ''[[Velocitermes]]''. Other inhabitants of the plant include [[Castniidae|giant butterfly-moths]], [[hoverfly|hoverflies]], [[beetle]]s, [[pseudoscorpion]]s, [[springtail]]s, and [[spider]]s.<ref>Schmid, V. S., et al. (2014). [http://www.hindawi.com/journals/psyche/2014/396095/ Inflorescences of the bromeliad ''Vriesea friburgensis'' as nest sites and food resources for ants and other arthropods in Brazil.] ''Psyche'' 2014 396095.</ref>
