{{Infobox person |name = James K. Guthrie |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = 11 March 1914 <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |birth_place = |death_date = {{d-da|9 March 1996|11 March 1914}} <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = |occupation=symphony conductor and newspaper executive }}
'''James Kelley Guthrie''' (March 11, 1914 &ndash; March 9, 1996)<ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/James-Guthrie-1914-1996-Social-Security-Death-Index/10802010148462698291 JAMES GUTHRIE (1914&ndash;1996), Social Security Death Index]</ref> was an American symphony [[Conducting|conductor]] and newspaper executive.<ref name=pe>{{cite news|url= http://www.pe.com/columns/markmuckenfuss/stories/PE_News_Local_N_nmark27.22649cf.html|title=San Bernardino Symphony hits 80th year|last= Muckenfuss|first=Mark |coauthors= |date=September 26, 2008|work=The Press-Enterprise|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref>
At the age of 15, he founded the [[San Bernardino Community Orchestra]], which is today the [[San Bernardino Symphony]].<ref name=pe /><ref name=time>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,757102,00.html|title= Music: Youngest Conductor |date=December 7, 1936|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref>
In 1936, after Guthrie conducted the first performance of the [[Hollywood Grand Opera Association]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called him the "youngest full-fledged symphony conductor in the U. S."<ref name="time"/>
He was the owner and publisher of the ''[[San Bernardino Sun]]'' newspaper from 1964 until 1979. In 1974, he established the [[Guthrie Music Rental Library]], which rents "scores and orchestra music to thousands of schools, colleges, and orchestras (both major and new struggling orchestras) at affordable prices in order to encourage music performance."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guthriemusiclibrary.com/guthrie.html|title=Who was James K. Guthrie|work=Guthrie Music Rental Library|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref> From 1964 until 1973, he was the conductor of the [[Riverside Symphony Orchestra]] in [[Riverside, California]], later known as the [[Inland Empire Symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riversideca.gov/LIBRARY/history_aids_rivsymphony.asp|title=Riverside Symphony Orchestra Program Collection |work=Riverside Public Library|accessdate= December 16, 2009}}</ref>
