{{Infobox football biography | name = Nevi Gebreselasie | image = | fullname = Nevi Ghebremeskez Gebreselasie | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Eritrea]] | height = | currentclub = | clubnumber = | position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2011 | years2 = 2011–2013 | years3 = 2013 | years4 = 2014 | years5 = 2016 | clubs1 = [[Western Strikers]] | clubs2 = [[White City Woodville]] | clubs3 = [[Adelaide Cobras]] | clubs4 = [[Adelaide Olympic FC|Adelaide Olympic]] | clubs5 = [[Northern Demons SC|Northern Demons]] | caps1 = 3 | caps2 = 24 | caps3 = 6 | caps4 = 19 | caps5 = 10 | goals1 = 0 | goals2 = 8 | goals3 = 0 | goals4 = 4 | goals5 = 4 | nationalyears1 = 2009 | nationalteam1 = [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]] | nationalcaps1 = ? | nationalgoals1 = ? | pcupdate = 30 August 2013 | ntupdate = 21 September 2011 }}
'''Nevi Gebreselasie''' is an [[Eritrea]]n footballer who last played for [[Adelaide Cobras]].
==Club career== In 2011, he signed with [[South Australian Super League|FFSA Super League]] club [[Western Strikers]] after being granted refugee status by the Australian government.<ref name="adelaidenow.com.au">http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/out-of-africa-its-a-whole-new-ball-game/story-e6frecj3-1226036645661 Out of Africa, it's a whole new ball game</ref> He later signed for [[South Australian Premier League|FFSA Premier League]] side [[White City Woodville]] scoring 3 goals in 5 games.
==International career== He played in the [[2009 CECAFA Cup]] in [[Kenya]], appearing in the 2-1 group match defeat to [[Rwanda national football team|Rwanda]].<ref name="michezonet">{{Cite news |url=http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83%3Arwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35%3Ademo-content2&Itemid=29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082222/http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83:rwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35:demo-content2&Itemid=29 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 July 2011 |title=Rwanda through to Quarter Finals |last=Okinyo |first=Collins |date=4 December 2009 |publisher=michezo net |accessdate=16 December 2009 }}</ref>
==Personal life==
Whilst competing in the [[2009 CECAFA Cup]] in [[Kenya]] he was part of the [[Eritrea national football team]] which failed to return home after competing in the regional tournament in [[Nairobi]].<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/12/15/football.cecafa.eritrea.kenya/index.html 12 Eritrean soccer players sought in Kenya</ref> After receiving political asylum from the Australian government, the team moved to [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]].<ref name="adelaidenow.com.au"/>
