{{Infobox football biography | name = Samuel Tesfagabr | image = | fullname = Samuel Ghebrehiwet Tesfagabr | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|5|5|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Khartoum]], Sudan | height = 185 cm | currentclub = [[West Adelaide SC|West Adelaide]] | clubnumber = | position = [[Defender (association football)|Left Back]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2011 | years2 = 2011–2012 | years3 = 2012–2015 | years4 = 2016 | years5 = 2017 | years6 = 2017– | clubs1 = [[Western Strikers]] | clubs2 = [[Gold Coast United]] | clubs3 = [[Adelaide Comets]] | clubs4 = [[Adelaide Blue Eagles]] | clubs5 = [[Adelaide Olympic FC|Adelaide Olympic]] | clubs6 = [[West Adelaide SC|West Adelaide]] | caps1 = 14 | caps2 = 0 | caps3 = 70 | caps4 = 23 | caps5 = 7 | caps6 = 10 | goals1 = 1 | goals2 = 0 | goals3 = 20 | goals4 = 3 | goals5 = 0 | goals6 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2009 | nationalteam1 = [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]] | nationalcaps1 = ? | nationalgoals1 = ? | pcupdate = 21 August 2017 | ntupdate = 24 September 2012 }}
'''Samuel Tesfagabr''' is an [[Eritrea]]n [[Association football|footballer]]. He defected from Eritrea while on national team duty at a tournament in Kenya and received asylum in Australia. He was signed to the [[A-League]] team [[Gold Coast United]] in their final season. As of 2016, he plays for [[Adelaide Blue Eagles]] in the [[National Premier Leagues South Australia]].
==Escape from Eritrea== Tesfagabr was part of the [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]] and played in the [[2009 CECAFA Cup]] in [[Kenya]], appearing in the 2-1 group match defeat to [[Rwanda national football team|Rwanda]].<ref name="michezonet">{{Cite news |url=http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83%3Arwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35%3Ademo-content2&Itemid=29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082222/http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83:rwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35:demo-content2&Itemid=29 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 July 2011 |title=Rwanda through to Quarter Finals |last=Okinyo |first=Collins |date=4 December 2009 |publisher=michezo net |accessdate=16 December 2009 }}</ref> When the team plane returned, none of the players including Tesfagabr were on it sparking a search by Eritrean authorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eritrea football team 'absconds' in Kenya| publisher=BBC|date=14 December 2009|accessdate=19 October 2016|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8412651.stm}}</ref> Tesfagabr and his teammates avoided detection for ten days in Nairobi before finding their way to a refugee camp 800&nbsp;km from the Kenyan capital. They spent eight months at the camp before they were granted refugee status by Australia.<ref name=anow>{{cite news|title= Mehari Tesema and Samuel Tesfagabr become Australian citizens five years after fleeing from Eritrean national soccer team|publisher=Adelaide Now|date=4 February 2015|author=Rob Greenwood|accessdate= 19 October 2016}}</ref> After receiving refugee status from the Australian government, the team moved to [[Adelaide]].<ref name=anow2>{{cite news|title=Out of Africa, it's a whole new ball game|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/out-of-africa-its-a-whole-new-ball-game/story-e6frecj3-1226036645661|date=10 April 2011|publisher=Adelaide Now|accessdate=19 October 2016|author=Jai Bednall|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908183955/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/out-of-africa-its-a-whole-new-ball-game/story-e6frecj3-1226036645661|archivedate=8 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Career in Australia== After moving to Australia, Tesfagabr, and three other Eritreans signed with the [[Western Strikers SC]] of [[South Australian Super League|FFSA Super League]]. While playing for the club, he worked for a local switchboard manufacturer.<ref name=anow2/> For the 2011-12 season, he, along with fellow Eritrean refugee [[Ambesager Yosief]], signed with [[A-League]] club [[Gold Coast United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A-League preview of teams|author=Val Migliaccio|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/a-league-teams/story-e6frfkp9-1226159079369|publisher=news.co.au|accessdate=19 October 2016|date=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|title=Western Strikers Eritrean duo sign for GCU - Channel 10 report|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FpmhBT7kfL4|date=6 September 2011|accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref> Tesfagabr did not make an official appearance for the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary: S. Tesfagabr|publisher=Soccerway|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/samuel-tesfagabr/212050/|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref> At the end of the season, Gold Coast United lost their license and were dissolved.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/soccer/a-league-revokes-gold-coast-licence/story-e6frfg8x-1226285137642 |title=A-League revokes Gold Coast licence |newspaper=Herald Sun |date=29 February 2012 |publisher=Herald and Weekly Times |location=Melbourne}}</ref> For the 2013 season, he signed with the [[Adelaide Comets]] of the FFSA Super League.<ref name=anow/> In 2016, he made a move to the previous season's runner-up [[Adelaide Blue Eagles]] in the same league, which is now called [[National Premier Leagues South Australia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SA Premier League soccer season kicks off tonight |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/messenger/sport/sa-premier-league-soccer-season-kicks-off-tonight/news-story/e6adf33d712277c4a43fa262be9c65b3|author=Rob Greenwood|date=5 February 2016| accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref>
Tesfagabr became an Australian citizen in 2015.<ref name=anow/>
