{{Infobox football biography | name = Jamal Mahamud | image = | fullname = Jemal Abdu Mahamud | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Eritrea]] | height = | currentclub = | clubnumber = | position = [[Midfielder]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2011–2012 | clubs1 = [[Croydon Kings]] | caps1 = 13 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2012–2013 | clubs2 = [[Adelaide Comets]] | caps2 = 7 | goals2 = 0 | years3 = 2013–2014 | clubs3 = [[Western Strikers]] | caps3 = 36 | goals3 = 1 | nationalyears1 = 2009 | nationalteam1 = [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]] | nationalcaps1 = ? | nationalgoals1 = ? | pcupdate = 14 September 2014 | ntupdate = 18 May 2012 }}
'''Jemal Abdu''' is an [[Eritrea]]n footballer who last played for the [[Western Strikers]] in the [[FFSA Super League]].
==Club career== In 2011, he signed with [[South Australian Super League|FFSA Super League]] club [[Croydon Kings]] after being granted political asylum by the Australian government.<ref name="adelaidenow.com.au">http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/out-of-africa-its-a-whole-new-ball-game/story-e6frecj3-1226036645661 Out of Africa, it's a whole new ball game</ref>
==International career== Abdu played in the [[2009 CECAFA Cup]] in [[Kenya]], appearing in the 2-1 group match defeat to [[Rwanda national football team|Rwanda]].<ref name="michezonet">{{Cite news |url=http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83%3Arwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35%3Ademo-content2&Itemid=29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082222/http://michezonet.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83:rwanda-through-to-quarter-finals&catid=35:demo-content2&Itemid=29 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 July 2011 |title=Rwanda through to Quarter Finals |last=Okinyo |first=Collins |date=4 December 2009 |publisher=michezo net |accessdate=16 December 2009 }}</ref>
==Personal life==
Whilst competing in the [[2009 CECAFA Cup]] in [[Kenya]] he was part of the [[Eritrea national football team]] which failed to return home after competing in the regional tournament in [[Nairobi]].<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/12/15/football.cecafa.eritrea.kenya/index.html 12 Eritrean soccer players sought in Kenya</ref> After receiving political asylum from the Australian government, the team moved to [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]].<ref name="adelaidenow.com.au"/>
