'''Jean-Louis Millette''' ({{IPA-fr|ʒɑ̃ lwi milɛt}}; 4 January 1935 in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]] &ndash; 29 September 1999 in Montreal) was a French-speaking actor and writer.<ref name=Mtl/>
Millette's television career spans over thirty years: he was a cast member of many of the best-known series in Quebec, including the children's series ''[[La Ribouldingue]]'' (which he also co-wrote), ''[[L'Héritage]]'', ''[[Symphorien (television series)|Symphorien]]'' and ''[[Montréal P.Q. (television series)|Montréal P.Q.]]'' (in a role which earned him a [[Prix Gémeaux]] in 1994).<ref name=Mtl>{{Cite web|url=http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=5238,23621567&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&pageType=2&id_comedien=2|title=Jean-Louis Millette (1935 - 1999) |publisher=City of Montreal's website about "La Roulotte"|language=French|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|reason=source lists Imdb as a source|date=December 2017}} He was also the voice of [[Abraham Simpson]], [[Apu Nahasapeemapetilon]] and [[Waylon Smithers]] in the Quebec dubbing of ''[[The Simpsons]]''. On the big screen, he played mostly supporting roles, most notably in [[Robert Lepage]]'s first film ''[[The Confessional]] (Le Confessionnal)''.
However, Millette's most significant work was in theatre: he was a major figure of Quebec theatre and, in 1990, received the [[Prix Victor-Morin]] for outstanding achievement in theatre in Quebec. He was a member of the [[Théâtre de Quat'Sous]] when it was founded by [[Paul Buissonneau]] in 1956.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fse.uqam.ca/milieuxdefavorises/serie_C/13.html|title=Biographie de Jean-Louis Millette |date=1999-09-30|publisher=Presse Canadienne|language=French|accessdate=16 December 2009}}{{dead link|date=December 2017}}</ref> Millette died suddenly of a [[heart attack]] in September 1999. At the time, he was touring a one-man performance of [[Larry Tremblay]]'s ''[[The Dragonfly of Chicoutimi]]''. This role had earned him the [[Masque Prize]] (Quebec's annual prizes in theatre) for best acting performance.
